Popular Stability or PS was formed as a splinter off of the AfF in opposition to the AfF's declaration of support for imediate Sahellan independence. In the war for Sahellan independence it was members of Popular Stability, utilising their connections with the French government and international circles to open up backchannel peace discussions, which culminated in the signing of the Venice Accords. Despite significant dislike of PS by the leaders of the NEF the AfF was able to secure PS's entry into the congress.

PS draws its support from two broad groups, the first are the old middle class, industrialists and other wealthy individuals, a significant number also being French settlers. The second group are the Mabota, encouraged by PS's talk of Federalism. However the two populations which support PS are far from aligned, however the catastrophic consequences of splitting now has dissuaded both sides from instigating such an action for now.

