= The nominees for Minister for the Economy are...

The Ministry for the Economy is responsible for both expenditure and revenue of the Sahellan government, it also plays a significant role in economic and trade policy. Amongst the delegates gathered there have been over ten nominations for Minister for the Economy, but after a prelimenary round only four nominees remain.

The first is Jean Biya, a member of PS who's central argument and pitch is the renogotiation of trade treaties with France and the forging of new trade ties with the United States. Biya is also an advocate for the extensive modernisation of the Agricultural sector to free up labour and provide food to support his proposed industrialisation plans.

The second is John Daouda, a member of the AfF who advocates for greater trade with the whole world. Daouda advocates for tax cuts and land redistrobution to the rural poor, Daouda intends to afford his policies via the state aquiring many now derelict properties and businesses of recently fled French nationals and selling them to native Sahellans.

The third is Peter Njume, a member of the NEF's Marxist wing who has proposed a sweeping plan for state ownership over the economy, and intensive industrialisation efforts similar to the "Great Leap Forward" taking place in the PRC under Mao Zedong.

The forth is Georges Iswana, also a member of the NEF however part of the Agrarian wing Iswana pushes for a "managed capitalism" which assists rural and regional farmers by guaranteing a stable price to sell their food at, which according to Iswana will reduce the urban-rural divide and drive more equal economic growth. Iswana also places a greater emphasis on trade between fellow African countries than the other contendors. 

The question then lies with you, Monsiuer President, who will you appoint?

