= The candidates under discussion for Foreign Minister present themselves

The Foreign Ministry controls all matters of affairs between Sahella and other Nations, it will be pivotal to Sahella's efforts in establishing itself within the international community, and the striking of new trade deals with potential partners. The choice of Foreign Minister will reflect which side you are taking in regards to discussion more broadley about Sahella's place in the world, particularly poignant is what relation Sahella should have with her former colonial overlord. After significant back and forth four candidates present themselves as options.

The first is Samuel Akoghet, a member of the AfF who advocates for closer ties with Sahella's African neighbours and the United States, Akoghet's hostility to communism and the Soviet Union may assist in his dealings with the United States but will equally harm his ability to close potential trade deals with the Eastern Bloc. His key position on France is one of mutual disassociation, with France and Sahella reestablishing diplomatic relations but cooperating no further.

The second in Raymond Chambrier, the controversial figure within PS who's connections both to the previous colonial regime and the French government was instrumental in establishing a dialogue for the eventual Venice Accords. Deeply hostile to Marxism appointing Chambrier would torpedo any previous relations Sahella had, however he would also be able to use his experience and connections with the Western Bloc to more easily negotiate trade deals with them. The most outspoken member at the Congress Chambrier also advocates for close cooperation with France and the many multinationals who remain in business in Sahella.

The third is Ephraim Shafeta of the NEF, who proposes seeking closer ties with the Eastern Bloc, the repudiation of all ties with France and unusually friendly relations with Mao Zedong's PRC. It seems almost certain that appointing Shafeta will push the United States and other members of the Western Bloc away from Sahella, which may result in further slowdowns in the economy. On the upside however is that Shafeta's virilant anti-French rhetoric is likely to be popular and preserve the legitamacy of the government.

Then there is Anton Sheya, the non-partisan former Deputy Secretary of the previous colonial regime. His politics is largely unknown however he did resign his post in protest after the leak of the colonial regimes torture blacksites to the public. Sheya could represent a stable experienced hand, making no friends but provoking no enemies, however his previous affiliation with the colonial government may prove unpopular.

